1. Malware Upload

Users may upload infected files (virus, ransomware, trojan).
If downloaded later, it can harm other users or the system.

2. Unauthorized Access

If cloud storage permissions are misconfigured:

Files may become public.

Sensitive data can leak.

3. Data Breach

Without encryption:

Uploaded files can be intercepted.

Confidential information may be exposed.

4. File Type Exploits

Attackers can upload:

Executable files (.exe, .php, .js)

Script files that may run on the server
This can lead to Remote Code Execution (RCE).

5. Denial of Service (DoS)

Large or multiple file uploads may:

Overload server storage

Increase cloud costs

Crash the application

6. Broken Access Control

If access control is weak:

One user may access another user’s files.

7. Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)

If file URLs are predictable:

Attackers can guess file paths

Download private files